# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polymer-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In polymer chemistry, a **copolymer** is a polymer derived from more than one species of monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The polymerization of monomers into copolymers is called **copolymerization**.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Copolymers obtained from the copolymerization of two monomer species are sometimes called *bipolymers*.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Those obtained from three and four monomers are called ***terpolymers*** and *quaterpolymers*, respectively.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Copolymers can be characterized by a variety of techniques such as NMR spectroscopy and size-exclusion chromatography to determine the molecular size, weight, properties, and composition of the material.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Commercial copolymers include acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), styrene/butadiene co-polymer (SBR), nitrile rubber, styrene-acrylonitrile, styrene-isoprene-styrene (SIS) and ethylene-vinyl acetate, all of which are formed by chain-growth polymerization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Another production mechanism is step-growth polymerization, which is used to produce the nylon-12/6/66 copolymer of nylon 12, nylon 6 and nylon 66, as well as the copolyester family.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Copolymers can be used to develop commercial goods or drug delivery vehicles.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Since a copolymer consists of at least two types of constituent units (also structural units), copolymers can be classified based on how these units are arranged along the chain.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] *Linear copolymers* consist of a single main chain and include alternating copolymers, statistical copolymers, and block copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] *Branched copolymers* consist of a single main chain with one or more polymeric side chains, and can be grafted, star shaped, or have other architectures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The *reactivity ratio* of a growing copolymer chain terminating in a given monomer is the ratio of the reaction rate constant for addition of the same monomer and the rate constant for addition of the other monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The composition and structural type of the copolymer depend on these reactivity ratios r1 and r2 according to the Mayo–Lewis equation, also called the **copolymerization equation** or **copolymer equation**, for the relative instantaneous rates of incorporation of the two monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Due to the wide variety of copolymers possible, there is no single accepted naming convention, but IUPAC has a general suggested naming scheme that indicates the organization of repeat units within a copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In this convention, source based nomenclature is used to indicate the monomers from which the copolymer was synthesized.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Following the IUPAC naming conventions, a generally copolymer is named poly(A-*co*-B), where A and B are the monomers and -*co*- represents the type of copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] This linkers changes with the type of copolymers, examples of which are shown below.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] If the exact structure of the polymer is unknown, the linker -*co*- should be used.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For nonlinear or branched copolymers, a prefix indicating the type of non-linearity is added prior to the copolymer naming.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Given the wide range of potential branched polymers, if the branching pattern is unknown, the general prefix branch is used.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Examples of other prefixes are shown below.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Block copolymers comprise two or more homopolymer subunits linked by covalent bonds.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The union of the homopolymer subunits may require an intermediate non-repeating subunit, known as a **junction block**.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] **Diblock copolymers** have two distinct blocks; **triblock copolymers** have three.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Technically, a block is a portion of a macromolecule, comprising many units, that has at least one feature which is not present in the adjacent portions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A possible sequence of repeat units A and B in a triblock copolymer might be ~A-A-A-A-A-A-A-B-B-B-B-B-B-B-A-A-A-A-A~.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Block copolymers are made up of blocks of different polymerized monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For example, polystyrene-b-poly(methyl methacrylate) or PS-b-PMMA (where b = block) is usually made by first polymerizing styrene, and then subsequently polymerizing methyl methacrylate (MMA) from the reactive end of the polystyrene chains.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] This polymer is a "diblock copolymer" because it contains two different chemical blocks.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Triblocks, tetrablocks, multiblocks, etc. can also be made.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Diblock copolymers are made using living polymerization techniques, such as atom transfer free radical polymerization (ATRP), reversible addition fragmentation chain transfer (RAFT), ring-opening metathesis polymerization (ROMP), and living cationic or living anionic polymerizations.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] An emerging technique is chain shuttling polymerization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The synthesis of block copolymers requires that both reactivity ratios are much larger than unity (r1 >> 1, r2 >> 1) under the reaction conditions, so that the terminal monomer unit of a growing chain tends to add a similar unit most of the time.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The "**blockiness**" of a copolymer is a measure of the adjacency of comonomers vs their statistical distribution.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Many or even most synthetic polymers are in fact copolymers, containing about 1-20% of a minority monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In such cases, blockiness is undesirable.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A *block index* has been proposed as a quantitative measure of blockiness or deviation from random monomer composition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] An alternating copolymer has regular alternating A and B units, and is often described by the formula: -A-B-A-B-A-B-A-B-A-B-, or -(-A-B-)n-.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The molar ratio of each monomer in the polymer is normally close to one, which happens when the reactivity ratios r1 and r2 are close to zero, as can be seen from the Mayo–Lewis equation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For example, in the free-radical copolymerization of styrene maleic anhydride copolymer, r1 = 0.097 and r2 = 0.001, so that most chains ending in styrene add a maleic anhydride unit, and almost all chains ending in maleic anhydride add a styrene unit.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] This leads to a predominantly alternating structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A step-growth copolymer -(-A-A-B-B-)n- formed by the condensation of two bifunctional monomers A–A and B–B is in principle a perfectly alternating copolymer of these two monomers, but is usually considered as a homopolymer of the dimeric repeat unit A-A-B-B.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] An example is nylon 66 with repeat unit -OC-( CH2)4-CO-NH-(CH2)6-NH-, formed from a dicarboxylic acid monomer and a diamine monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Periodic copolymers have units arranged in a repeating sequence.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For two monomers A and B, for example, they might form the repeated pattern (A-B-A-B-B-A-A-A-A-B-B-B)n.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In statistical copolymers the sequence of monomer residues follows a statistical rule.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] If the probability of finding a given type monomer residue at a particular point in the chain is equal to the mole fraction of that monomer residue in the chain, then the polymer may be referred to as a truly **random copolymer** (structure 3).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Statistical copolymers are dictated by the reaction kinetics of the two chemically distinct monomer reactants, and are commonly referred to interchangeably as "random" in the polymer literature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] As with other types of copolymers, random copolymers can have interesting and commercially desirable properties that blend those of the individual homopolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Examples of commercially relevant random copolymers include rubbers made from styrene-butadiene copolymers and resins from styrene-acrylic or methacrylic acid derivatives.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A number of parameters are relevant in the composition of the polymer product; namely, one must consider the reactivity ratio of each component.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Reactivity ratios describe whether the monomer reacts preferentially with a segment of the same type or of the other type.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For example, a reactivity ratio that is less than one for component 1 indicates that this component reacts with the other type of monomer more readily.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Given this information, which is available for a multitude of monomer combinations in the "Wiley Database of Polymer Properties", the Mayo-Lewis equation can be used to predict the composition of the polymer product for all initial mole fractions of monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] This equation is derived using the Markov model, which only considers the last segment added as affecting the kinetics of the next addition; the Penultimate Model considers the second-to-last segment as well, but is more complicated than is required for most systems.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] When both reactivity ratios are less than one, there is an azeotropic point in the Mayo-Lewis plot.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] At this point, the mole fraction of monomer equals the composition of the component in the polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] There are several ways to synthesize random copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The most common synthesis method is free radical polymerization; this is especially useful when the desired properties rely on the composition of the copolymer rather than the molecular weight, since free radical polymerization produces relatively disperse polymer chains.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Free radical polymerization is less expensive than other methods, and produces high-molecular weight polymer quickly.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Several methods offer better control over dispersity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Anionic polymerization can be used to create random copolymers, but with several caveats: if carbanions of the two components do not have the same stability, only one of the species will add to the other.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Additionally, anionic polymerization is expensive and requires very clean reaction conditions, and is therefore difficult to implement on a large scale.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Less disperse random copolymers are also synthesized by ″living″ controlled radical polymerization methods, such as atom-transfer radical-polymerization (ATRP), nitroxide mediated radical polymerization (NMP), or reversible addition−fragmentation chain-transfer polymerization (RAFT).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] These methods are favored over anionic polymerization because they can be performed in conditions similar to free radical polymerization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The reactions require longer experimentation periods than free radical polymerization, but still achieve reasonable reaction rates.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In stereoblock copolymers the blocks or units differ only in the tacticity of the monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In gradient copolymers the monomer composition changes gradually along the chain.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] There are a variety of architectures possible for nonlinear copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Beyond grafted and star polymers discussed below, other common types of branched copolymers include **brush copolymers** and **comb copolymers**.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Graft copolymers are a special type of branched copolymer wherein the side chains are structurally distinct from the main chain.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Typically, the main chain is formed from one type of monomer (A) and branches are formed from another monomer (B), or the side-chains have constitutional or configurational features that differ from those in the main chain.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The individual chains of a graft copolymer may be homopolymers or copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Note that different copolymer sequencing is sufficient to define a structural difference, thus an A-B diblock copolymer with A-B alternating copolymer side chains is properly called a graft copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For example, polystyrene chains may be grafted onto polybutadiene, a synthetic rubber which retains one reactive C=C double bond per repeat unit.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The polybutadiene is dissolved in styrene, which is then subjected to free-radical polymerization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The growing chains can add across the double bonds of rubber molecules forming polystyrene branches.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The graft copolymer is formed in a mixture with ungrafted polystyrene chains and rubber molecules.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] As with block copolymers, the quasi-composite product has properties of both "components." In the example cited, the rubbery chains absorb energy when the substance is hit, so it is much less brittle than ordinary polystyrene.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The product is called high-impact polystyrene, or HIPS.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Star (co)polymers are branched (co)polymers in which several polymer chains are connected to a central core.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Block copolymers can "microphase separate" to form periodic nanostructures, such as styrene-butadiene-styrene block copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The polymer is known as Kraton and is used for shoe soles and adhesives.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Owing to the microfine structure, transmission electron microscope or TEM was used to examine the structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The butadiene matrix was stained with osmium tetroxide to provide contrast in the image.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The material was made by living polymerization so that the blocks are almost monodisperse to create a regular microstructure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The molecular weight of the polystyrene blocks in the main picture is 102,000; the inset picture has a molecular weight of 91,000, producing slightly smaller domains.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Microphase separation is a situation similar to that of oil and water.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Oil and water are immiscible (i.e., they can phase separate).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Due to the incompatibility between the blocks, block copolymers undergo a similar phase separation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Since the blocks are covalently bonded to each other, they cannot demix macroscopically like water and oil.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In "microphase separation," the blocks form nanometer-sized structures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Depending on the relative lengths of each block, several morphologies can be obtained.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In diblock copolymers, sufficiently different block lengths lead to nanometer-sized spheres of one block in a matrix of the second (e.g., PMMA in polystyrene).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Using less different block lengths, a "hexagonally packed cylinder" geometry can be obtained.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Blocks of similar length form layers (often called lamellae in the technical literature).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Between the cylindrical and lamellar phase is the gyroid phase.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The nanoscale structures created from block copolymers can potentially be used to create devices for computer memory, nanoscale-templating, and nanoscale separations.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Block copolymers are sometimes used as a replacement for phospholipids in model lipid bilayers and liposomes for their superior stability and tunability.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Polymer scientists use thermodynamics to describe how the different blocks interact.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The product of the degree of polymerization, *n*, and the Flory-Huggins interaction parameter, $\chi$ , gives an indication of how incompatible the two blocks are and whether they will microphase separate.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] For example, a diblock copolymer of symmetric composition will microphase separate if the product $\chi N$ is greater than 10.5.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] If $\chi N$ is less than 10.5, the blocks will mix and microphase separation is not observed.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The incompatibility between the blocks also affects the solution behavior of these copolymers and their adsorption behavior on various surfaces.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Block copolymers are able to self-assemble in selective solvents to form micelles among other structures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] In thin films, block copolymers are of great interest as masks in the lithographic patterning of semiconductor materials for applications in high density data storage.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A key challenge is to minimise the feature size and much research is in progress on this.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Characterization techniques for copolymers are similar to those for other polymeric materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] These techniques can be used to determine the average molecular weight, molecular size, chemical composition, molecular homogeneity, and physiochemical properties of the material.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] However, given that copolymers are made of base polymer components with heterogeneous properties, this may require multiple characterization techniques to accurately characterize these copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Spectroscopic techniques, such as nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy (NMR), infrared spectroscopy (IR), and UV spectroscopy, are often used to identify the molecular structure and chemical composition of copolymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] NMR can be used to determine a number of polymer characteristics, including tacticity and repeat unit sequence, predominantly using 1H and 13C NMR.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] NMR can also be used for analysis of the end groups and branching points within polymer chains, which can provide information both about size and branching pattern.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] IR spectroscopy is primarily used to identify functional groups attached to a copolymer, but it can also provide information about the degree of branching within a copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] UV spectroscopy can be used to determine the concentration of a chromophore-containing monomer within a polymer resin.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] UV spectroscopy is commonly used as a detector with size-exclusion chromatography.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Scattering techniques, such as static light scattering, dynamic light scattering, and small-angle neutron scattering, can determine the molecular size and weight of the synthesized copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Static light scattering and dynamic light scattering use light to determine the average molecular weight and behavior of the copolymer in solution whereas small-angle neutron scattering uses neutrons to determine the molecular weight and chain length.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Additionally, x-ray scattering techniques, such as small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) can help determine the nanometer morphology and characteristic feature size of a microphase-separated block-copolymer or suspended micelles.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Differential scanning calorimetry is a thermoanalytical technique used to determine the thermal events of the copolymer as a function of temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] It can indicate when the copolymer is undergoing a phase transition, such as crystallization or melting, by measuring the heat flow required to maintain the material and a reference at a constantly increasing temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Thermogravimetric analysis is another thermoanalytical technique used to access the thermal stability of the copolymer as a function of temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] This provides information on any changes to the physicochemical properties, such as phase transitions, thermal decompositions, and redox reactions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Size-exclusion chromatography can separate copolymers with different molecular weights based on their hydrodynamic volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] From there, the molecular weight can be determined by deriving the relationship from its hydrodynamic volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Larger copolymers tend to elute first as they do not interact with the column as much.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The collected material is commonly detected by light scattering methods, a refractometer, or a viscometer to determine the concentration of the eluted copolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] A common application of block copolymers is to develop thermoplastic elastomers (TPEs).
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Early commercial TPEs were developed from polyurethranes (TPUs), consisting of alternating soft segments and hard segments, and are used in automotive bumpers and snowmobile treads.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Styrenic TPEs entered the market later, and are used in footwear, bitumen modification, thermoplastic blending, adhesives, and cable insulation and gaskets.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Modifying the linkages between the blocks resulted in newer TPEs based on polyesters (TPES) and polyamides (TPAs), used in hose tubing, sport goods, and automotive components.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Amphiphilic block copolymers have the ability to form micelles and nanoparticles.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Due to this property, amphiphilic block copolymers have garnered much attention in research on vehicles for drug delivery.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Similarly, amphiphilic block copolymers can be used for the removal of organic contaminants from water either through micelle formation or film preparation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] The styrene-maleic acid (SMA) alternating copolymer displays amphiphilicity depending on pH, allowing it to change conformations in different environments.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Some conformations that SMA can take are random coil formation, compact globular formation, micelles, and nanodiscs.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] SMA has been used as a dispersing agent for dyes and inks, as drug delivery vehicles, and for membrane solubilization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Copolymerization is used to modify the properties of manufactured plastics to meet specific needs, for example to reduce crystallinity, modify glass transition temperature, control wetting properties or to improve solubility.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] It is a way of improving mechanical properties, in a technique known as rubber toughening.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Elastomeric phases within a rigid matrix act as crack arrestors, and so increase the energy absorption when the material is impacted for example.
[src:polymer-chemistry/copolymer] Acrylonitrile butadiene styrene is a common example.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In chemistry and biology, a **cross-link** is a bond or a short sequence of bonds that links one polymer chain to another.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] These links may take the form of covalent bonds or ionic bonds and the polymers can be either synthetic polymers or natural polymers (such as proteins).
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In polymer chemistry "cross-linking" usually refers to the use of cross-links to promote a change in the polymers' physical properties.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] When "crosslinking" is used in the biological field, it refers to the use of a probe to link proteins together to check for protein–protein interactions, as well as other creative cross-linking methodologies.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Although the term is used to refer to the "linking of polymer chains" for both sciences, the extent of crosslinking and specificities of the crosslinking agents vary greatly.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Crosslinking generally involves covalent bonds that join two polymer chains.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The term *curing* refers to the crosslinking of thermosetting resins, such as unsaturated polyester and epoxy resin, and the term *vulcanization* is characteristically used for rubbers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] When polymer chains are crosslinked, the material becomes more rigid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The mechanical properties of a polymer depend strongly on the cross-link density.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Low cross-link densities increase the viscosities of polymer melts.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Intermediate cross-link densities transform gummy polymers into materials that have elastomeric properties and potentially high strengths.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Very high cross-link densities can cause materials to become very rigid or glassy, such as phenol-formaldehyde materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In one implementation, unpolymerized or partially polymerized resin is treated with a **crosslinking reagent**.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In vulcanization, sulfur is the cross-linking agent.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Its introduction changes rubber to a more rigid, durable material associated with car and bike tires.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] This process is often called sulfur curing.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In most cases, cross-linking is irreversible, and the resulting thermosetting material will degrade or burn if heated, without melting.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Chemical covalent cross-links are stable mechanically and thermally.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Therefore, cross-linked products like car tires cannot be recycled easily.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] A class of polymers known as thermoplastic elastomers rely on physical cross-links in their microstructure to achieve stability, and are widely used in non-tire applications, such as snowmobile tracks, and catheters for medical use.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] They offer a much wider range of properties than conventional cross-linked elastomers because the domains that act as cross-links are reversible, so can be reformed by heat.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The stabilizing domains may be non-crystalline (as in styrene-butadiene block copolymers) or crystalline as in thermoplastic copolyesters.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Alkyd enamels, the dominant type of commercial oil-based paint, cure by oxidative crosslinking after exposure to air.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In contrast to chemical cross-links, physical cross-links are formed by weaker interactions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] For example, sodium alginate gels upon exposure to calcium ions, which form ionic bonds that bridge between alginate chains.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Polyvinyl alcohol gels upon the addition of borax through hydrogen bonding between boric acid and the polymer's alcohol groups.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Other examples of materials which form physically cross-linked gels include gelatin, collagen, agarose, and agar agar.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Crosslinking is often measured by swelling tests.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The crosslinked sample is placed into a good solvent at a specific temperature, and either the change in mass or the change in volume is measured.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The more crosslinking, the less swelling is attainable.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Based on the degree of swelling, the Flory Interaction Parameter (which relates the solvent interaction with the sample), and the density of the solvent, the theoretical degree of crosslinking can be calculated according to Flory's Network Theory.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Two ASTM standards are commonly used to describe the degree of crosslinking in thermoplastics.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In ASTM D2765, the sample is weighed, then placed in a solvent for 24 hours, weighed again while swollen, then dried and weighed a final time.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The degree of swelling and the soluble portion can be calculated.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In another ASTM standard, F2214, the sample is placed in an instrument that measures the height change in the sample, allowing the user to measure the volume change.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The crosslink density can then be calculated.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Lignin is a highly crosslinked polymer that comprises the main structural material of higher plants.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] A hydrophobic material, it is derived from precursor monolignols.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Heterogeneity arises from the diversity and degree of crosslinking between these lignols.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Intrastrand DNA crosslinks have strong effects on organisms because these lesions interfere with transcription and replication.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] These effects can be put to good use (addressing cancer) or they can be lethal to the host organism.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The drug cisplatin functions by formation of intrastrand crosslinks in DNA.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Other crosslinking agents include mustard gas, mitomycin, and psoralen.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In proteins, crosslinks are important in generating mechanically stable structures such as hair and wool, skin, and cartilage.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Isopeptide bond formation is another type of protein crosslink.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The process of applying a permanent wave to hair involves the breaking and reformation of disulfide bonds.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Typically a mercaptan such as ammonium thioglycolate is used for the breaking.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Following this, the hair is curled and then "neutralized".
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The neutralizer is typically an acidic solution of hydrogen peroxide, which causes new disulfide bonds to form, thus permanently fixing the hair into its new configuration.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Compromised collagen in the cornea, a condition known as keratoconus, can be treated with clinical crosslinking.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In biological context crosslinking could play a role in atherosclerosis through advanced glycation end-products (AGEs), which have been implicated to induce crosslinking of collagen, which may lead to vascular stiffening.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Proteins can also be cross-linked artificially using small-molecule crosslinkers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] This approach has been used to elucidate protein–protein interactions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Crosslinkers bind only surface residues in relatively close proximity in the native state.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Common crosslinkers include the imidoester crosslinker dimethyl suberimidate, the N-Hydroxysuccinimide-ester crosslinker BS3 and formaldehyde.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Each of these crosslinkers induces nucleophilic attack of the amino group of lysine and subsequent covalent bonding via the crosslinker.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] The zero-length carbodiimide crosslinker EDC functions by converting carboxyls into amine-reactive isourea intermediates that bind to lysine residues or other available primary amines.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] SMCC or its water-soluble analog, Sulfo-SMCC, is commonly used to prepare antibody-hapten conjugates for antibody development.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] An *in-vitro* cross-linking method is PICUP (photo-induced cross-linking of unmodified proteins).
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Typical reagents are ammonium persulfate (APS), an electron acceptor, the photosensitizer tris-bipyridylruthenium (II) cation ([Ru(bpy)3]2+).
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] In *in-vivo* crosslinking of protein complexes, cells are grown with photoreactive diazirine analogs to leucine and methionine, which are incorporated into proteins.
[src:polymer-chemistry/cross-link] Upon exposure to ultraviolet light, the diazirines are activated and bind to interacting proteins that are within a few ångströms of the photo-reactive amino acid analog (UV cross-linking).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The **glass–liquid transition**, or **glass transition**, is the gradual and reversible transition in amorphous materials (or in amorphous regions within semicrystalline materials) from a hard and relatively brittle "glassy" state into a viscous or "rubbery" state as the temperature is increased.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] An amorphous solid that exhibits a glass transition is called a glass.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The reverse transition, achieved by supercooling a viscous liquid into the glass state, is called vitrification.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The **glass-transition temperature** *T*g of a material characterizes the range of temperatures over which this glass transition occurs (as an experimental definition, typically marked as 100 s of relaxation time).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] It is always lower than the melting temperature, *T*m, of the crystalline state of the material, if one exists, because the glass is a higher energy state (or enthalpy at constant pressure) than the corresponding crystal.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Hard plastics like polystyrene and poly(methyl methacrylate) are used well below their glass transition temperatures, i.e., when they are in their glassy state.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Their *T*g values are both at around 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Rubber elastomers like polyisoprene and polyisobutylene are used above their *T*g, that is, in the rubbery state, where they are soft and flexible; crosslinking prevents free flow of their molecules, thus endowing rubber with a set shape at room temperature (as opposed to a viscous liquid).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Despite the change in the physical properties of a material through its glass transition, the transition is not considered a phase transition; rather it is a phenomenon extending over a range of temperature and defined by one of several conventions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Such conventions include a constant cooling rate (20 kelvins per minute (36 °F/min)) and a viscosity threshold of 1012 Pa·s, among others.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Upon cooling or heating through this glass-transition range, the material also exhibits a smooth step in the thermal-expansion coefficient and in the specific heat, with the location of these effects again being dependent on the history of the material.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The question of whether some phase transition underlies the glass transition is a matter of ongoing research.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The glass transition of a liquid to a solid-like state may occur with either cooling or compression.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The transition comprises a smooth increase in the viscosity of a material by as much as 17 orders of magnitude within a temperature range of 500 K without any pronounced change in material structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This transition is in contrast to the freezing or crystallization transition, which is a first-order phase transition in the Ehrenfest classification and involves discontinuities in thermodynamic and dynamic properties such as volume, energy, and viscosity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In many materials that normally undergo a freezing transition, rapid cooling will avoid this phase transition and instead result in a glass transition at some lower temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Other materials, such as many polymers, lack a well defined crystalline state and easily form glasses, even upon very slow cooling or compression.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The tendency for a material to form a glass while quenched is called glass forming ability.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This ability depends on the composition of the material and can be predicted by the rigidity theory.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Below the transition temperature range, the glassy structure does not relax in accordance with the cooling rate used.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The expansion coefficient for the glassy state is roughly equivalent to that of the crystalline solid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] If slower cooling rates are used, the increased time for structural relaxation (or intermolecular rearrangement) to occur may result in a higher density glass product.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Similarly, by annealing (and thus allowing for slow structural relaxation) the glass structure in time approaches an equilibrium density corresponding to the supercooled liquid at this same temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] *T*g is located at the intersection between the cooling curve (volume versus temperature) for the glassy state and the supercooled liquid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The configuration of the glass in this temperature range changes slowly with time towards the equilibrium structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The principle of the minimization of the Gibbs free energy provides the thermodynamic driving force necessary for the eventual change.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] At somewhat higher temperatures than *T*g, the structure corresponding to equilibrium at any temperature is achieved quite rapidly.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In contrast, at considerably lower temperatures, the configuration of the glass remains sensibly stable over increasingly extended periods of time.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Thus, the liquid-glass transition is not a transition between states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] It is widely believed that the true equilibrium state is always crystalline.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Glass is believed to exist in a kinetically locked state, and its entropy, density, and so on, depend on the thermal history.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, the glass transition is primarily a dynamic phenomenon.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Time and temperature are interchangeable quantities (to some extent) when dealing with glasses, a fact often expressed in the time–temperature superposition principle.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] On cooling a liquid, *internal degrees of freedom successively fall out of equilibrium*.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, there is a longstanding debate whether there is an underlying second-order phase transition in the hypothetical limit of infinitely long relaxation times.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In anisotropic-particle fluids, such as ellipsoid fluids, different degrees of freedom can fall out of equilibrium separately.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Calculations based on mode-coupling theory for the glass transition predicted, for hard ellipsoids, an orientational, or rotational, glass transition in which particle orientations become arrested while center-of-mass motion can remain quasi-ergodic.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Molecular dynamics simulations of a soft ellipsoid fluid later reproduced this behaviour, supporting the view that colloidal liquid glass is a rotationally arrested state distinct from the conventional glassy state described in this article, in which translation motion is arrested.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As a result of the fluctuating input of thermal energy into the liquid matrix, the harmonics of the oscillations are constantly disturbed and temporary cavities ("free volume") are created between the elements, the number and size of which depend on the temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature *T*g0 defined in this way is a fixed material constant of the disordered (non-crystalline) state that is dependent only on the pressure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As a result of the increasing inertia of the molecular matrix when approaching *T*g0, the setting of the thermal equilibrium is successively delayed, so that the usual measuring methods for determining the glass transition temperature in principle deliver *T*g values that are too high.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In principle, the slower the temperature change rate is set during the measurement, the closer the measured *T*g value *T*g0 approaches.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Techniques such as dynamic mechanical analysis can be used to measure the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The definition of the glass and the glass transition are not settled, and many definitions have been proposed over the past century.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Franz Simon: Glass is a rigid material obtained from freezing-in a supercooled liquid in a narrow temperature range.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Zachariasen: Glass is a topologically disordered network, with short range order equivalent to that in the corresponding crystal.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Glass is a "frozen liquid" (i.e., liquids where ergodicity has been broken), which spontaneously relax towards the supercooled liquid state over a long enough time.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Glasses are thermodynamically non-equilibrium kinetically stabilized amorphous solids, in which the molecular disorder and the thermodynamic properties corresponding to the state of the respective under-cooled melt at a temperature *T** are frozen-in.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Hereby *T** differs from the actual temperature *T*.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Glass is a nonequilibrium, non-crystalline condensed state of matter that exhibits a glass transition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The structure of glasses is similar to that of their parent supercooled liquids (SCL), and they spontaneously relax toward the SCL state.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Their ultimate fate is to solidify, i.e., crystallize.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Refer to the figure on the bottom right plotting the heat capacity as a function of temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In this context, *T*g is the temperature corresponding to point A on the curve.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Different operational definitions of the glass transition temperature *T*g are in use, and several of them are endorsed as accepted scientific standards.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Nevertheless, all definitions are arbitrary, and all yield different numeric results: at best, values of *T*g for a given substance agree within a few kelvins.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] One definition refers to the viscosity, fixing *T*g at a value of 1013 poise (or 1012 Pa·s).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As evidenced experimentally, this value is close to the annealing point of many glasses.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In contrast to viscosity, the thermal expansion, heat capacity, shear modulus, and many other properties of inorganic glasses show a relatively sudden change at the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Any such step or kink can be used to define *T*g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] To make this definition reproducible, the cooling or heating rate must be specified.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The most frequently used definition of *T*g uses the energy release on heating in differential scanning calorimetry (DSC, see figure).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Typically, the sample is first cooled with 10 K/min and then heated with that same speed.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Yet another definition of *T*g uses the kink in dilatometry (a.k.a. thermal expansion): refer to the figure on the top right.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Here, heating rates of 3–5 K/min (5.4–9.0 °F/min) are common.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The linear sections below and above *T*g are colored green.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] *T*g is the temperature at the intersection of the red regression lines.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Summarized below are *T*g values characteristic of certain classes of materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Dry nylon-6 has a glass transition temperature of 47 °C (117 °F).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Nylon-6,6 in the dry state has a glass transition temperature of about 70 °C (158 °F).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Polyethylene has a glass transition range of −130 to −80 °C (−202 to −112 °F).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The above are only approximate values, as the glass transition temperature depends on the cooling rate and molecular weight distribution and could be influenced by additives.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] For a semi-crystalline material, such as polyethylene that is 60–80% crystalline at room temperature, the quoted glass transition refers to what happens to the amorphous part of the material upon cooling.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In 1971, Zeller and Pohl discovered that when glass is at a very low temperature ~1K, its specific heat has a linear component: $c\approx c_{1}T+c_{3}T^{3}$ .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This is an unusual effect, because crystal material typically has $c\propto T^{3}$ , as in the Debye model.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This was explained by the two-level system hypothesis, which states that a glass is populated by two-level systems, which look like a double potential well separated by a wall.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The wall is high enough such that resonance tunneling does not occur, but thermal tunneling does occur.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Namely, if the two wells have energy difference $\Delta E\sim k_{B}T$ , then a particle in one well can tunnel to the other well by thermal interaction with the environment.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Consider a single two-level system that is not frozen-out, whose energy gap is $\Delta E=O(1/\beta )$ .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] It is in a Boltzmann distribution, so its average energy $={\frac {\beta \Delta E}{e^{\beta \Delta E}-1}}\beta ^{-1}$ .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Now, assume that the two-level systems are all quenched, so that each $\Delta E$ varies little with temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In that case, we can write $n(\Delta E)$ as the density of states with energy gap $\Delta E$ .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] We also assume that $n(\Delta E)$ is positive and smooth near $\Delta E\approx 0$ .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The effect is that the average energy in these two-level systems is ${\bar {E}}\sim T^{2}$ , leading to a $\partial _{T}{\bar {E}}\propto T$ term.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In experimental measurements, the specific heat capacity of glass is measured at different temperatures, and a $(T^{2},c/T)$ graph is plotted.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Assuming that $c\approx c_{1}T+c_{3}T^{3}$ , the graph should show $c/T\approx c_{1}+c_{3}T^{2}$ , that is, a straight line with slope showing the typical Debye-like heat capacity, and a vertical intercept showing the anomalous linear component.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Modern studies of glass-forming materials suggest that the slowing of dynamics near the glass-transition temperature is accompanied by increasing spatial heterogeneity in molecular motion.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Experimental and simulation studies suggest that molecular motion near the glass-transition temperature becomes spatially heterogeneous.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Instead of all segments slowing down uniformly, regions of relatively high mobility coexist with regions that are significantly less mobile, a phenomenon known as dynamic heterogeneity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As temperature approaches the glass-transition temperature, structural relaxation increasingly occurs through cooperative rearrangements involving groups of molecules or polymer segments, and the size of these cooperatively rearranging regions grows as the temperature decreases.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Experimental evidence for dynamic heterogeneity has been obtained using techniques such as dielectric spectroscopy, multidimensional nuclear magnetic resonance, and single-molecule fluorescence measurements, all of which reveal spatial variations in relaxation dynamics near the glass transition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Molecular dynamics simulations similarly show spatially correlated motion and string-like rearrangements of particles in supercooled liquids and polymer systems approaching the glass transition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Dynamic heterogeneity has been proposed as an explanation for several features of glass-forming polymers, including non-exponential relaxation behavior, deviations from time–temperature superposition, and departures from simple free-volume descriptions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] These observations support the view that the glass transition is governed by cooperative dynamics rather than purely local segmental motion.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As a liquid is supercooled, the difference in entropy between the liquid and solid phase decreases.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] By extrapolating the heat capacity of the supercooled liquid below its glass transition temperature, it is possible to calculate the temperature at which the difference in entropies becomes zero.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This temperature has been named the **Kauzmann temperature**.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] If a liquid could be supercooled below its Kauzmann temperature, and it did indeed display a lower entropy than the crystal phase, this would be paradoxical, as the liquid phase should have the same vibrational entropy, but much higher positional entropy, as the crystal phase.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This is the **Kauzmann paradox**, still not definitively resolved.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] There are many possible resolutions to the Kauzmann paradox.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Kauzmann himself resolved the entropy paradox by postulating that all supercooled liquids must crystallize before the Kauzmann temperature is reached.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Perhaps at the Kauzmann temperature, glass reaches an ideal glass *phase*, which is still amorphous, but has a long-range amorphous order which decreases its overall entropy to that of the crystal.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The ideal glass would be a true phase of matter.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The ideal glass is hypothesized, but cannot be observed naturally, as it would take too long to form.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Something approaching an ideal glass has been observed as "ultrastable glass" formed by vapor deposition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Perhaps there must be a phase transition before the entropy of the liquid decreases.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In this scenario, the transition temperature is known as the *calorimetric ideal glass transition temperature* *T*0c.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In this view, the glass transition is not merely a kinetic effect, i.e. merely the result of fast cooling of a melt, but there is an underlying thermodynamic basis for glass formation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Perhaps the heat capacity of the supercooled liquid near the Kauzmann temperature smoothly decreases to a smaller value.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Perhaps first order phase transition to another liquid state occurs before the Kauzmann temperature with the heat capacity of this new state being less than that obtained by extrapolation from higher temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Time temperature superposition curve is a very powerful tool for the analysis of polymeric and rheological materials near the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] One of the key uses of time temperature superposition (TTS) curves it to extrapolate the long term viscoelastic behavior of materials using the experimental data for the short term viscoelastic behavior of materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, it can provide key information for the design of polymeric materials over varying time scales and temperature scales (including the glass transition temperature.).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As a class of materials, TTS curves are very useful for understanding the behavior of polymeric materials because of their viscoelastic behavior where the flow and the deformation of the material is dependent on both the time and temperature of the material.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] For example, consider the behavior of a typical polymer subjected to a constant load.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] You would expect the strain/ deformation of the materials increases with time as the system tends to minimize local stresses by rearranging the molecular configuration.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, any short term measurements of the mechanical performance will provide a significantly lower or higher value depending on the property being measured.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] One method to determine the desired properties/ mechanical performance of the material is to study the behavior of the material at the exact temperature or time period that is of interest.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, if the time periods or temperatures required are very high, this method can quickly become very expensive in terms of time consumed and the cost.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, TTS curves provide an excellent tool to effectively predict the long term rheology of polymeric materials utilizing data for their short term behavior.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Time temperature superposition curves, which is also known as the method of reduced variables is based on two key principles/ assumptions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The first assumption is that an increase in temperature results in an increase in the frequency with which molecular rearrangements occur in viscoelastic materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, at high temperatures, the deformation and strain will vary at a much higher rate than at relatively low temperatures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The second assumption is that there is a direct equivalency between the temperature and time (frequency).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In other words, the effects of increasing the temperature are directly equivalent to the effects of increasing the time scale in terms of their impact on the viscoelastic behavior of polymeric materials.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Therefore, if the deformation and strain behavior of a polymeric material are collected over a small time period at a high temperature, the resulting data can be shifted to determine the behavior of the material for a specific temperature over a much larger time scale.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This resultant curve which is determined after the shifting is known as the master curve.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] There are numerous different models which can be utilized to determine the amount of shift required to project the experimental curve in order to arrive at the master curve.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, the two most common models are the Williams Landels Ferry (WLF) model and the Arrhenius equation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The figure above shows a general time temperature superposition plot where the x axis is defined as the log(time) and the y axis is defined as the creep compliance.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Typically, y axis is either creep compliance or the elastic/ storage modulus (G').
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] From the figure above, it can be observed that the short term creep plots are shifted along the x-axis in order to obtain the master curve.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This x-axis shift can be determined using the WLF equation or the Arrhenius equation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The equation above describes the WLF equation where log At represents the x-axis shift required to obtain the master curve.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The reference temperature is the temperature at which the master curve is obtained whereas the other temperature variable T represents the temperature at which the short-term creep compliance data is collected.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The Williams Landels Ferry is most useful and accurate for understanding the time - temperature behavior of polymeric materials near the glass transition region because of the in-built assumptions of the model.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The WLF equation is based on the free volume theory of materials for glass transitions.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The first is that there is a linear, increasing relationship between the fractional free volume of the material and the temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The second assumption is that as the free volume of the material increases, the viscosity drops rapidly as there is more volume for particles to move (easier flow).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Within free volume theory, the empirical constants 𝐶1 and 𝐶2 in the Williams Landels Ferry equation can be interpreted in terms of the temperature dependence of fractional free volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Molecular mobility in polymers is assumed to depend exponentially on the inverse of the available fractional free volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] If the fractional free volume increases approximately linearly with temperature above the glass-transition temperature 𝑇𝑔, the constants 𝐶1 and 𝐶2 can be related to the fractional free volume at 𝑇𝑔 and the thermal expansion coefficient of the free volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The other model to determine the shift is the Arrhenius model which is more accurate for temperatures further away from the glass transition region.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The equation below describes the Arrhenius model where E is the activation energy and R is the ideal gas constant.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The temperature variables T and Tref refer to the measurement temperature and the reference temperature respectively.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Another important use of the Arrhenius model is to determine the activation energy of a polymeric material near the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Although the WLF equation is a more accurate near the glass transition temperature, it can directly be utilized to estimate the activation energy of the material.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Silica (the chemical compound SiO2) has a number of distinct crystalline forms in addition to the quartz structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Nearly all of the crystalline forms involve tetrahedral SiO4 units linked together by *shared vertices* in different arrangements (stishovite, composed of linked SiO6 octahedra, is the main exception).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Si-O bond lengths vary between the different crystal forms.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The Si-O-Si bond angle also varies from 140° in α-tridymite to 144° in α-quartz to 180° in β-tridymite.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Any deviations from these standard parameters constitute microstructural differences or variations that represent an approach to an amorphous, vitreous or glassy solid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The transition temperature *T*g in silicates is related to the energy required to break and re-form covalent bonds in an amorphous (or random network) lattice of covalent bonds.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The *T*g is clearly influenced by the chemistry of the glass.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] For example, addition of elements such as B, Na, K or Ca to a silica glass, which have a valency less than 4, helps in breaking up the network structure, thus reducing the *T*g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Alternatively, P, which has a valency of 5, helps to reinforce an ordered lattice, and thus increases the *T*g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] For strong melts such as Si*O*2 the percolation threshold in the above equation is the universal Scher–Zallen critical density in the 3-D space e.g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] *f*c = 0.15, however for fragile materials the percolation thresholds are material-dependent and *f*c ≪ 1.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The enthalpy *H*d and the entropy *S*d of configurons – broken bonds can be found from available experimental data on viscosity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] On the surface of SiO2 films, scanning tunneling microscopy has resolved clusters of ca.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] 5 SiO2 in diameter that move in a two-state fashion on a time scale of minutes.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This is much faster than dynamics in the bulk, but in agreement with models that compare bulk and surface dynamics.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In polymers the glass transition temperature, *T*g, is often expressed as the temperature at which the Gibbs free energy is such that the activation energy for the cooperative movement of 50 or so elements of the polymer is exceeded .
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This allows molecular chains to slide past each other when a force is applied.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] From this definition, we can see that the introduction of relatively stiff chemical groups (such as benzene rings) will interfere with the flowing process and hence increase *T*g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The stiffness of thermoplastics decreases due to this effect (see figure.) When the glass temperature has been reached, the stiffness stays the same for a while, i.e., at or near *E*2, until the temperature exceeds *T*m, and the material melts.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This region is called the rubber plateau.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In ironing, a fabric is heated through this transition so that the polymer chains become mobile.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The weight of the iron then imposes a preferred orientation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] *T*g can be significantly decreased by addition of plasticizers into the polymer matrix.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Smaller molecules of plasticizer embed themselves between the polymer chains, increasing the spacing and free volume, and allowing them to move past one another even at lower temperatures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Addition of plasticizer can effectively take control over polymer chain dynamics and dominate the amounts of the associated free volume so that the increased mobility of polymer ends is not apparent.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The addition of nonreactive side groups to a polymer can also make the chains stand off from one another, reducing *T*g.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] If a plastic with some desirable properties has a *T*g that is too high, it can sometimes be combined with another in a copolymer or composite material with a *T*g below the temperature of intended use.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Note that some plastics are used at high temperatures, e.g., in automobile engines, and others at low temperatures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In viscoelastic materials, the presence of liquid-like behavior depends on the properties of and so varies with rate of applied load, i.e., how quickly a force is applied.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The silicone toy Silly Putty behaves quite differently depending on the time rate of applying a force: pull slowly and it flows, acting as a heavily viscous liquid; hit it with a hammer and it shatters, acting as a glass.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] On cooling, rubber undergoes a *liquid-glass transition*, which has also been called a *rubber-glass transition*.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Polymer blending is a process in which two or more polymers are mixed together in order to create a new polymer with properties which are significantly different from the properties of the individual polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The blending process can result in enhanced properties like superior strength or flexibility for a variety of applications like packaging, automotive parts and electronics.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] There are various different classifications of polymer blends but in the discussion of the effect on glass transitions I will classify polymer blends as miscible and immiscible.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Miscibility refers to the mixing of the individual polymers at a molecular level.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] While miscible polymers mix favorably, immiscible polymers remain separate within the blend at a molecular level.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The miscibility of polymers has an impact on the glass transition region of the polymer blends.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Typically, for immiscible polymer blends, the glass transition temperature of the polymer doesn't change with the composition and it maintains the same glass transition temperature region as the bulk value of the polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Most polymers are thermodynamically immiscible in nature due to their low configurational entropy of mixing.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Immiscible polymer blends are commonly produced using a technique called melt processing, which allows for production at a very low cost.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] At the molecular level, the phases in the blend of the individual polymers remain separate which is why the individual polymers maintain the same glass transition temperature / region as in their pure form.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In immiscible polymer blends, the separation of the phases for the individual polymers results in distinct glass transition temperature for the individual phases.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Using either differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) or Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA), the glass transition temperature of immiscible polymer blends can be revealed.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The results should show two or more distinct peaks depending on the number of separate phases in the immiscible polymer blend.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The presence of this distinct and individual glass transition temperature peaks indicates phase separation and can also be utilized to classify whether a polymer blend is immiscible or not.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] On the other hand, for miscible polymer blends in which the individual polymers mix favorably and completely, there is a single glass transition temperature which is typical in between the glass transition temperatures of the individual polymer Tg values.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, the glass transition temperature of the doesn't always have to be in between the individual Tg values.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature of the miscible polymer blend is influenced by the composition and individual Tg values of the polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The flory-fox equation/ model can be used to estimate the glass transition temperature of a miscible polymer blend to a good degree of accuracy when there are strong interactions between the individual polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The fox model assumes that the mixing is ideal and that the chains are fully interspersed, which is why it only works accurately when there are strong interactions between the individual polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The equation below describes the Fox equation where w is the weight fraction of the individual polymer and Tg represents the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Bulk metallic glasses (BMGs) are intrinsically amorphous alloys.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] But while traditional amorphous alloys are typically formed at high cooling rates in order to suppress the nucleation of the crystalline phases, BMGs can be formed at lower critical cooling rates.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The high cooling rates needed for the formation of traditional amorphous alloys restricts the form of the finished product to powders, films, depositions and ribbons.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In comparison to the wide range of different types of glasses, BMGs have superior properties in terms of amorphous character and high mechanical strength.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, the most unique characteristic of BMGs is their glass transition behavior.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] As metallic glasses are cooled from high to low temperatures, they transform from a supercooled liquid state into a glassy state and vice versa.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Scientifically, metallic glasses are defined as amorphous alloys which exhibit a glass transition.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This glass transition allows the materials to have a high strength at low temperatures and a very high flexibility at high temperatures due to the abrupt change in the physical and thermal properties of the material at the glass transition temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Regardless of the atomic configurations, it has been generally accepted by experts that the disorder of metallic glass can only be conserved down to a certain length scale.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Atoms in metallic glasses tend to form short range order in which the local nearest neighbor environment of each atom is similar to other equivalent atoms, but this regularity doesn't persist over an appreciable distance.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Due to the fact that good glass formers have a higher density than ordinary amorphous alloys with high critical cooling rates, it is recommended to have a composition with high packing density for good glass forming ability.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The figure 1c shows a differential scanning calorimetry of a bulk metallic glass sample, illustrating the glass transition and the presence of a wide supercooled liquid region.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The supercooled liquid region is defined in terms of the glass transition temperature (Tg) and the crystallization temperature (Tx).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The glass transition temperature represents the temperature below which the material becomes a rigid amorphous solid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Between the glass transition temperature and the crystallization temperature the material is in a supercooled liquid state.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] A wider supercooled liquid region allows easier formation of glass without unwanted crystallization and increases the probability of forming a more stable amorphous structure during rapid cooling.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Finally, the supercooled liquid region gives the material polymer-like forming capabilities (i.e. shaped, molded or formed like thermoplastics) while exhibiting the superior performance characteristics of metals at higher temperatures.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The supercooled liquid region is the key property of metallic glasses that makes it useful for applications such as biomedical implants.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Molecular motion in condensed matter can be represented by a Fourier series whose physical interpretation consists of a superposition of longitudinal and transverse waves of atomic displacement with varying directions and wavelengths.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In monatomic systems, these waves are called *density fluctuations*.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Thus, thermal motion in liquids can be decomposed into elementary longitudinal vibrations (or acoustic phonons) while transverse vibrations (or shear waves) were originally described only in elastic solids exhibiting the highly ordered crystalline state of matter.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] In other words, simple liquids cannot support an applied force in the form of a shearing stress, and will yield mechanically via macroscopic plastic deformation (or viscous flow).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Furthermore, the fact that a solid deforms locally while retaining its rigidity – while a liquid yields to macroscopic viscous flow in response to the application of an applied shearing force – is accepted by many as the mechanical distinction between the two.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The inadequacies of this conclusion, however, were pointed out by Frenkel in his revision of the kinetic theory of solids and the theory of elasticity in liquids.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This revision follows directly from the continuous characteristic of the viscoelastic crossover from the liquid state into the solid one when the transition is not accompanied by crystallization—ergo the supercooled viscous liquid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Thus we see the intimate correlation between transverse acoustic phonons (or shear waves) and the onset of rigidity upon vitrification, as described by Bartenev in his mechanical description of the vitrification process.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The velocities of longitudinal acoustic phonons in condensed matter are directly responsible for the thermal conductivity that levels out temperature differentials between compressed and expanded volume elements.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Kittel proposed that the behavior of glasses is interpreted in terms of an approximately constant "mean free path" for lattice phonons, and that the value of the mean free path is of the order of magnitude of the scale of disorder in the molecular structure of a liquid or solid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The thermal phonon mean free paths or relaxation lengths of a number of glass formers have been plotted versus the glass transition temperature, indicating a linear relationship between the two.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] This has suggested a new criterion for glass formation based on the value of the phonon mean free path.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] It has often been suggested that heat transport in dielectric solids occurs through elastic vibrations of the lattice, and that this transport is limited by elastic scattering of acoustic phonons by lattice defects (e.g. randomly spaced vacancies).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] These predictions were confirmed by experiments on commercial glasses and glass ceramics, where mean free paths were apparently limited by "internal boundary scattering" to length scales of 10–100 micrometres (0.00039–0.00394 in).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The influence of thermal phonons and their interaction with electronic structure is a topic that was appropriately introduced in a discussion of the resistance of liquid metals.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Lindemann's theory of melting is referenced, and it is suggested that the drop in conductivity in going from the crystalline to the liquid state is due to the increased scattering of conduction electrons as a result of the increased amplitude of atomic vibration.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Such theories of localization have been applied to transport in metallic glasses, where the mean free path of the electrons is very small (on the order of the interatomic spacing).
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The formation of a non-crystalline form of a gold-silicon alloy by the method of splat quenching from the melt led to further considerations of the influence of electronic structure on glass forming ability, based on the properties of the metallic bond.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Other work indicates that the mobility of localized electrons is enhanced by the presence of dynamic phonon modes.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] One claim against such a model is that if chemical bonds are important, the nearly free electron models should not be applicable.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] However, if the model includes the buildup of a charge distribution between all pairs of atoms just like a chemical bond (e.g., silicon, when a band is just filled with electrons) then it should apply to solids.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Thus, if the electrical conductivity is low, the mean free path of the electrons is very short.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] The electrons will only be sensitive to the short-range order in the glass since they do not get a chance to scatter from atoms spaced at large distances.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Since the short-range order is similar in glasses and crystals, the electronic energies should be similar in these two states.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] For alloys with lower resistivity and longer electronic mean free paths, the electrons could begin to sense that there is disorder in the glass, and this would raise their energies and destabilize the glass with respect to crystallization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Thus, the glass formation tendencies of certain alloys may therefore be due in part to the fact that the electron mean free paths are very short, so that only the short-range order is ever important for the energy of the electrons.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] It has also been argued that glass formation in metallic systems is related to the "softness" of the interaction potential between unlike atoms.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Some authors, emphasizing the strong similarities between the local structure of the glass and the corresponding crystal, suggest that chemical bonding helps to stabilize the amorphous structure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Other authors have suggested that the electronic structure yields its influence on glass formation through the directional properties of bonds.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Non-crystallinity is thus favored in elements with a large number of polymorphic forms and a high degree of bonding anisotropy.
[src:polymer-chemistry/glass-transition] Crystallization becomes more unlikely as bonding anisotropy is increased from isotropic metallic to anisotropic metallic to covalent bonding, thus suggesting a relationship between the group number in the periodic table and the glass forming ability in elemental solids.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] In polymer chemistry, the **molar mass distribution** (or **molecular weight distribution**) describes the relationship between the number of moles of each polymer species (Ni) and the molar mass (Mi) of that species.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] In linear polymers, the individual polymer chains rarely have exactly the same degree of polymerization and molar mass, and there is always a distribution around an average value.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The molar mass distribution of a polymer may be modified by polymer fractionation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Different average values can be defined, depending on the statistical method applied.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Here, a is the exponent in the Mark–Houwink equation that relates the intrinsic viscosity to molar mass.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] These different definitions have true physical meaning because different techniques in physical polymer chemistry often measure just one of them.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] For instance, osmometry measures number average molar mass and small-angle laser light scattering measures mass average molar mass.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] *M*v is obtained from viscosimetry and *M*z by sedimentation in an analytical ultra-centrifuge.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The quantity a in the expression for the viscosity average molar mass varies from 0.5 to 0.8 and depends on the interaction between solvent and polymer in a dilute solution.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] In a typical distribution curve, the average values are related to each other as follows: $M_{n}<M_{v}<M_{w}<M_{z}.$ The dispersity (also known as the *polydispersity index*) of a sample is defined as *M*w divided by *M*n and gives an indication just how narrow a distribution is.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The most common technique for measuring molecular mass used in modern times is a variant of high-pressure liquid chromatography (HPLC) known by the interchangeable terms of size exclusion chromatography (SEC) and gel permeation chromatography (GPC).
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] These techniques involve forcing a polymer solution through a matrix of cross-linked polymer particles at a pressure of up to several hundred bar.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The limited accessibility of stationary phase pore volume for the polymer molecules results in shorter elution times for high-molecular-mass species.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The use of low dispersity standards allows the user to correlate retention time with molecular mass, although the actual correlation is with the Hydrodynamic volume.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] If the relationship between molar mass and the hydrodynamic volume changes (i.e., the polymer is not exactly the same shape as the standard) then the calibration for mass is in error.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The most common detectors used for size exclusion chromatography include online methods similar to the bench methods used above.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] By far the most common is the differential refractive index detector that measures the change in refractive index of the solvent.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] This detector is concentration-sensitive and very molecular-mass-insensitive, so it is ideal for a single-detector GPC system, as it allows the generation of mass v's molecular mass curves.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Less common but more accurate and reliable is a molecular-mass-sensitive detector using multi-angle laser-light scattering - see static light scattering.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] These detectors directly measure the molecular mass of the polymer and are most often used in conjunction with differential refractive index detectors.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The molar mass distribution of a polymer sample depends on factors such as chemical kinetics and work-up procedure.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Ideal step-growth polymerization gives a polymer with dispersity of 2.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Ideal living polymerization results in a dispersity of 1.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] By dissolving a polymer an insoluble high molar mass fraction may be filtered off resulting in a large reduction in *M*w and a small reduction in *M*n, thus reducing dispersity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The **number average molar mass** is a way of determining the molecular mass of a polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Polymer molecules, even ones of the same type, come in different sizes (chain lengths, for linear polymers), so the average molecular mass will depend on the method of averaging.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The *number average* molecular mass is the ordinary arithmetic mean or average of the molecular masses of the individual macromolecules.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The **mass average molar mass** (often loosely termed *weight average molar mass*) is another way of describing the molar mass of a polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] Some properties are dependent on molecular size, so a larger molecule will have a larger contribution than a smaller molecule.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The mass average molar mass is calculated by ${\bar {M}}_{w}={\frac {\sum _{i}N_{i}M_{i}^{2}}{\sum _{i}N_{i}M_{i}}}$ where Ni is the number of molecules of molecular mass Mi.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The mass average molecular mass can be determined by static light scattering, small angle neutron scattering, X-ray scattering, and sedimentation velocity.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The ratio of the *mass average* to the *number average* is called the dispersity or the *polydispersity* index.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The z-average molar mass can be determined with ultracentrifugation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/molar-mass-distribution] The melt elasticity of a polymer is dependent on *M*z.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] A **monomer** (/ˈmɒnəmər/ *MON-ə-mər*; *mono-*, "one" + *-mer*, "part") is a molecule that can react together with other monomer molecules to form a larger polymer chain or two- or three-dimensional network in a process called polymerization.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Chemistry classifies monomers by type, and two broad classes based on the type of polymer they form.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Differing stoichiometry causes each class to create its respective form of polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] The polymerization of one kind of monomer gives a homopolymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Many polymers are copolymers, meaning that they are derived from two different monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] In the case of condensation polymerizations, the ratio of comonomers is usually 1:1.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] For example, the formation of many nylons requires equal amounts of a dicarboxylic acid and diamine.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] In the case of addition polymerizations, the comonomer content is often only a few percent.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] For example, small amounts of 1-octene monomer are copolymerized with ethylene to give specialized polyethylene.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] The term "monomeric protein" may also be used to describe one of the proteins making up a multiprotein complex.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] For *proteins*, the monomers are amino acids.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Usually about 20 types of amino acid monomers are used to produce proteins.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] For polynucleic acids (DNA/RNA), the monomers are nucleotides, each of which is made of a pentose sugar, a nitrogenous base and a phosphate group.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Nucleotide monomers are found in the cell nucleus.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Four types of nucleotide monomers are precursors to DNA and four different nucleotide monomers are precursors to RNA.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] For carbohydrates, the monomers are monosaccharides.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] The most abundant natural monomer is glucose, which is linked by glycosidic bonds into the polymers cellulose, starch, and glycogen.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Isoprene is a natural monomer that polymerizes to form a natural rubber, most often *cis-*1,4-polyisoprene, but also *trans-*1,4-polymer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/monomer] Synthetic rubbers are often based on butadiene, which is structurally related to isoprene.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The work of Henri Braconnot in 1777 and the work of Christian Schönbein in 1846 led to the discovery of nitrocellulose, which, when treated with camphor, produced celluloid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Dissolved in ether or acetone, it becomes collodion, which has been used as a wound dressing since the U.S.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Cellulose acetate was first prepared in 1865.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] In years 1834-1844 the properties of rubber (polyisoprene) were found to be greatly improved by heating with sulfur, thus founding the vulcanization process.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] In 1884 Hilaire de Chardonnet started the first artificial fiber plant based on regenerated cellulose, or viscose rayon, as a substitute for silk, but it was very flammable.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] In 1907 Leo Baekeland invented the first polymer made independent of the products of organisms, a thermosetting phenol-formaldehyde resin called Bakelite.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Cellophane was invented in 1908 by Jocques Brandenberger who treated sheets of viscose rayon with acid.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The chemist Hermann Staudinger first proposed that polymers consisted of long chains of atoms held together by covalent bonds, which he called macromolecules.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] His work expanded the chemical understanding of polymers and was followed by an expansion of the field of polymer chemistry during which such polymeric materials as neoprene, nylon and polyester were invented.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Before Staudinger, polymers were thought to be clusters of small molecules (colloids), without definite molecular weights, held together by an unknown force.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Staudinger received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1953.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Wallace Carothers invented the first synthetic rubber called neoprene in 1931, the first polyester, and went on to invent nylon, a true silk replacement, in 1935.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Paul Flory was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1974 for his work on polymer random coil configurations in solution in the 1950s.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Stephanie Kwolek developed an aramid, or aromatic nylon named Kevlar, patented in 1966.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Karl Ziegler and Giulio Natta received a Nobel Prize for their discovery of catalysts for the polymerization of alkenes.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Heeger, Alan MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa were awarded the 2000 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the development of polyacetylene and related conductive polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polyacetylene itself did not find practical applications, but organic light-emitting diodes (OLEDs) emerged as one application of conducting polymers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Teaching and research programs in polymer chemistry were introduced in the 1940s.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] An Institute for Macromolecular Chemistry was founded in 1940 in Freiburg, Germany under the direction of Staudinger.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] In America, a Polymer Research Institute (PRI) was established in 1941 by Herman Mark at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn (now Polytechnic Institute of NYU).
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polymers are high molecular mass compounds formed by polymerization of monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] They are synthesized by the polymerization process and can be modified by the additive of monomers.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The additives of monomers change polymers mechanical property, processability, durability and so on.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The simple reactive molecule from which the repeating structural units of a polymer are derived is called a monomer.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] A polymer can be described in many ways: its degree of polymerisation, molar mass distribution, tacticity, copolymer distribution, the degree of branching, by its end-groups, crosslinks, crystallinity and thermal properties such as its glass transition temperature and melting temperature.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polymers in solution have special characteristics with respect to solubility, viscosity, and gelation.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Illustrative of the quantitative aspects of polymer chemistry, particular attention is paid to the number-average and weight-average molecular weights $M_{n}$ and $M_{w}$ , respectively.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The formation and properties of polymers have been rationalized by many theories including Scheutjens–Fleer theory, Flory–Huggins solution theory, Cossee–Arlman mechanism, Polymer field theory, Hoffman Nucleation Theory, Flory–Stockmayer theory, and many others.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The study of polymer thermodynamics helps improve the material properties of various polymer-based materials such as polystyrene (styrofoam) and polycarbonate.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Common improvements include toughening, improving impact resistance, improving biodegradability, and altering a material's solubility.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] As polymers get longer and their molecular weight increases, their viscosity tend to increase.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Thus, the measured viscosity of polymers can provide valuable information about the average length of the polymer, the progress of reactions, and in what ways the polymer branches.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polymers can be classified in many ways.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polymers, strictly speaking, comprise most solid matter: minerals (i.e. most of the Earth's crust) are largely polymers, metals are 3-d polymers, organisms, living and dead, are composed largely of polymers and water.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Biopolymers are the structural and functional materials that comprise most of the organic matter in organisms.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] One major class of biopolymers are proteins, which are derived from amino acids.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Polysaccharides, such as cellulose, chitin, and starch, are biopolymers derived from sugars.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] The polynucleic acids DNA and RNA are derived from phosphorylated sugars with pendant nucleotides that carry genetic information.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Synthetic polymers are the structural materials manifested in plastics, synthetic fibers, paints, building materials, furniture, mechanical parts, and adhesives.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Synthetic polymers may be divided into thermoplastic polymers and thermoset plastics.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Thermoplastic polymers include polyethylene, teflon, polystyrene, polypropylene, polyester, polyurethane, Poly(methyl methacrylate), polyvinyl chloride, nylons, and rayon.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Thermoset plastics include vulcanized rubber, bakelite, Kevlar, and polyepoxide.
[src:polymer-chemistry/polymer-chemistry] Almost all synthetic polymers are derived from petrochemicals.
